JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 3
IS  - 1
SP  - 133
EP  - 151
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - This article is a reexamination of the clearing and settlement process in financial markets (particularly the futures market) and its performance during the 1987 stock market crash. It provides both some institutional background and some conceptual perspective on the problems faced by the system during the week of October 19. Much of the discussion is based on the useful analogies that can be drawn between the clearinghouse and other financial intermediaries, such as banks and insurance companies. A major conclusion is that the Federal Reserve played a vital role in protecting the integrity of the clearing and settlements system during the crash.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/3.1.133
ER  - 



